7373284825043569962.voice_to_text: I am actually convinced that Kpop companies are doing this on purpose. Let me explain. So the main reason why they get trainee so young, it's not because, like, younger people are better at the arts. God knows that's not true, but instead, like, they're easier to manipulate to, to make malleable, to make into whatever product that the company wants these kids to be. They started producing and writing. And with talent comes power. It is much easier to manipulate someone when they know that they're mediocre, when you're constantly reminding them that they can't sing well, they can't dance well, and the company has the burden of hiding from the public that they can't actually sing well, they can't actually dance well, and that they can be replaced with another girl that's a blank slate. I think that some of the kids that are currently in Kpop had a lot of potential. And I also think that a lot of the training, even back in the day, but especially now, is more about breaking you so that you're convinced that you have to do whatever the grown folk around you are telling you to do. I don't think that K pop is actually training kids anymore to be able to sing and dance on stage. I think it's purely about breaking the kids. It was about breaking the kids this entire time, but now it's not even like, oh, we have to at least have two or three members that can sing really well, or two or three members that can dance really well and advertise how talented they are at this particular skill. And they all have their roles. They saw how SM kept saying that Taemin couldn't sing. Now Taemin is one of the best selling artist solo artist for SM Entertainment to the point that he was able to leave. He didn't need SM anymore. And I really think that is what these Kpop companies are fearful of. These idols having the power through their talents to just leave and not have to listen to everything that they say. But that is my conspiracy theory.

7371944378031689006.voice_to_text: I don't mean to ruin the fun or anything but to me this feels kinda disrespectful. K-Pop choreography takes from a bunch of different choreography and then puts it into one. So to take one person's vision and then to hate on specific parts of it just feels wrong. Whenever someone creates something, whether it's dance or anything, it has a strong connection to them personally because it's what they want to express with whatever fits the vibe or the music or whatever they're going for. So just because it doesn't matter what you want or what your vision is or what you think is right doesn't mean that it's bad or objectively anything. As someone who sometimes creates content related to K-Pop, (because I also make K-Pop dance videos) I think that we need to have more respect for the creative process in general. There’s a lot that goes into it and it’s not just someone who creates the final product. These are real people that are creating things and putting themselves in a position where they're likely to be judged by people who maybe don't understand what they're going for. So to make videos like this that aren't productively contributing to conversation or adding anything, and instead just judging what people already created, it stops people from creating what they authentically want to create or what they believe they want to express which is where real art comes from. So (again) I don't wanna be ruining the fun or be a Karen or anything, but I'm just saying, we need to have more respect for the people that are creating the artistry that we're consuming and enjoying, that's all.

7369621351239273771.voice_to_text: I'm very much against people bringing their big ass fucking bazooka sized cameras to concerts. However, it is never okay to lay hands on someone like that. But by just seeing someone at a concert next to you that has one of those cameras, you can't automatically assume that they are saucing. Now if there's added context to the situation where this saw saying was acting purposely rude or sitting in a seat that they weren't supposed to be in, or if they laid hands on this person first, I would understand. 7369343862051065130.voice_to_text: I saw this video being reposted and quote tweeted on Twitter because people were mad that he was promoting the tour. CRAZY! And everyone that's mad has this exact same sentiment: “oh the maniac-only fans”  or “all the locals” or “all the non fans are gonna buy tickets… “…and now I as a REAL fan…” “I'm worried that I'm not gonna be able to buy a ticket.” I've always found this sense of superiority in fan spaces to be really weird. This “oh I'm a real fan because I've been around for longer.” “oh I'm a real fan because I know their birthdays.” “I'm a real fan because I stream their music 24 hours a day.” I don't know if this is a hot take, but I don't think you're entitled to a concert ticket or merch or whatever just because you've been a fan for longer. 7367126852135062826.video_description: Text DONATE to 43428 to help Earthjustice protect wildlife from seismic air gun suveys. #seismic #whale #dolphins #ecotok #oilandgas #climatechange
7367126852135062826.voice_to_text: The oil and gas industry is profiting by setting off explosions in one of the world's biological hotspots. This is called seismic airgun surveying, and it's used to search the ocean for oil. A single ship can blast every 10 seconds, 24 hours a day, seven days a week, for months on end. The air guns are like mini cannons and the blast can exceed 235 decibels, which is hundreds of times more intense than a jet engine. A marine mammal in the vicinity would be deafened. Most of this is happening in the Gulf of Mexico, home to some of the world's most endangered species. The blasts can inflict permanent, even fatal, hearing damage on whales, dolphins, even affect the plankton that's the foundation of the ocean food web. The sound waves can be heard across the entire Gulf. This near constant level of noise can mask vital calls that marine mammals depend on to survive. The Biden administration has a chance to reign in this harmful activity. Unfortunately, it issued a new rule that would still allow extensive seismic testing in the Gulf of Mexico. The environmental law organization Earthjustice is asking the administration to change course and correct the rule, so that it protects Gulf wildlife from seismic air gun surveys. If you'd like to support this work please text DONATE to 43438

7364585613850414366.voice_to_text: so I made this tweet a couple days ago talking about the struggles of planning concert outfits when you have body image issues which got a lot more attention than I expected so I thought I would talk about it on here as well in Kpop we're already exposed to all these people whose whole job is to fit the beauty standard but then when you go to these events and then you see fans who also look like they could be idols it definitely has given me a lot more anxiety on the way that I perceive myself also know that feeling of looking up like concert fits for inspo and then seeing like all these people who are thin or just like don't have the flaws that you're insecure about and just like having to mentally prepare yourself that you are not gonna look that way and running through your head of like all the adjustments that you are gonna have to make to make yourself feel like you can pull it off it also doesn't help that I have gained a lot of weight and with that I've lost almost like all my confidence and I can barely make it out i told myself i wasn’t gonna cry💀 with that I wanted to relay some of the replies that I've gotten on my tweet and that is a reminder that these concerts and spaces that you're going to is somewhere where you should be having fun and feeling comfortable most of the kpop concerts I've gone to have the most supportive energy that I have ever experienced in my life like everyone is just throwing compliments of being friendly and being cute so for anyone who's struggling the same way that I do you deserve to look cute and feel cute and you definitely will
